`serial_write_string()` spins until COM1 says the transmitter FIFO is ready. That only becomes true after we run `serial_init()`. By dropping a `serial_write_string()` into `vfs_resolve()` you moved a serial call into code that’s executed while the kernel is still coming up – before the driver has been initialised – so `serial_write_char()` never sees the ready bit flip and the CPU sits in that `while (!serial_transmit_ready()) {}` loop forever. From the outside QEMU just looks as if it “crashed” during boot.

That’s why the machine dies even though you believed `vfs_resolve()` wouldn’t run until you typed `ls`. Something in the early boot path ended up touching it (for example, the shell’s first loop walks the same code when it prepares redirection parsing), and because the serial port wasn’t programmed yet the debug print locked the CPU.

For early‑boot logging you have two safer options:

1. Write to VGA (`console_write()` / `console_putc()`), which doesn’t depend on any extra init.
2. Gate the serial diagnostics behind a flag you flip in `serial_init()`, e.g.

```c
static bool g_serial_ready;

void serial_init(void) {
    …existing init…
    g_serial_ready = true;
}

void debug_serial(const char *msg) {
    if (!g_serial_ready) { return; }
    serial_write_string(msg);
}
```

and use `debug_serial()` in places like `vfs_resolve()`.

Once the serial driver is initialised, your `vfs_resolve` prints will work and QEMU will stop “crashing” at boot.

